Obama stops new oil drillings 
There will not be any new oil drillings within the next years off the coast of the U.S. federal state Florida in the golf of Mexico. 
A corresponding ban has passed the government in Washington, and revoked her earlier plans definitely with that. 
Also in front of the eastern seaboard new drillings remain forbidden for the time being. 
This informed Home Secretary Ken Salazar on Wednesday. 
Trigger for the strict ban which shall be at least valid for the next five years is the explosion of the drilling rig "Deepwater Horizon" in April. 
This the life cost and led to the greatest ecological disaster of the USA, president Barack Obama had signalled his readiness on pressure of the opposition and the industry to allow new drillings in the eastern part of the golf of Mexico before the accident, eleven workers. 
The supporters want to reduce the dependence of the USA of oil supplies from abroad with that. 
To this day, who takes the responsibility for the devastating oil pollution in the golf is not cleared in conclusion. 
The British energy group BP which is confronted with billion demands is in the centre of the criticism. 
An investigating committee on behalf of Obama shall present her results in the course of December. 
Home Secretary Ken Salazar had lifted the drilling stop imposed after the explosion in October. 
Different oil companies had immediately made applications for new drilling plans in the connection. 
With sharper controls and more severe safety regulations Obama and Salazar want to exclude a recent catastrophe. 
At present, the responsible control authority which had got after numerous corruption reproaches in disrepute is reformed basically. 
In parallel, Obama has announced to close lucrative tax loopholes for the oil and gas groups. 
The industry warns publicly now that the capacity in the golf would turn out considerably lower than till now by a stricter regulation. 
"The plans of the government" are the biggest brake for the growth of the oil and gas industry, the result of a current industry-specific survey is by the adviser company BDO still with the drilling ban on Wednesday. 
Moreover, the American Energy Alliance laments the uncertainty in the line of business: "Nobody knows what will change with the regulation exactly." 
Investments into new sponsorship schemes would be put off at the expense of the growth for the time being. 
